"The protocols that define what a piece of email looks like and how it moves from place to place never considered issues of abuse. Yet spam, or unwanted email, has become an epidemic. Everyone knows the dire statistics on the increase in the percentage of email that's classified as spam or its more malicious cousin, phishing. Software developers and system administrators have dedicated innumerable resources in both person hours and hardware to combat this most annoying of Internet phenomena. JD Falk of Return Path and Murray Kucherawy of Cloudmark provide an overview of the fight against spam, and the benefits of an immediate and efficient flow of complaint feedback directly from users to mailbox providers. Some have called the Unix operating system, released in the 1980s, a product that ‘got out before it was ready’. The same can be said of Internet email. The very protocols that define what a piece of email looks like and how it moves from place to place – protocols the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined – never considered issues of abuse. They didn't have to, back then; the entire Internet comprised a small community of users and systems, most of whom knew each other. Who would possibly want to abuse such a system, and to what end?"
